Here's a comprehensive cache layer implementation for user profile API responses:

## **In-Memory Cache Implementation**

```typescript
interface CacheEntry<T> {
  data: T;
  expiresAt: number;
}

class InMemoryCache<T> {
  private cache = new Map<string, CacheEntry<T>>();
  private ttl: number;

  constructor(ttlMs: number = 5 * 60 * 1000) {
    this.ttl = ttlMs;
  }

  set(key: string, data: T): void {
    this.cache.set(key, {
      data,
      expiresAt: Date.now() + this.ttl,
    });
  }

  get(key: string): T | null {
    const entry = this.cache.get(key);
    if (!entry) return null;

    if (Date.now() > entry.expiresAt) {
      this.cache.delete(key);
      return null;
    }
    return entry.data;
  }

  invalidate(key: string): void {
    this.cache.delete(key);
  }

  clear(): void {
    this.cache.clear();
  }
}
```

## **User Profile Service with Caching**

```typescript
interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  avatar?: string;
}

class UserProfileService {
  private cache: InMemoryCache<UserProfile>;
  private dbFetch: (id: string) => Promise<UserProfile>;

  constructor(dbFetchFn: (id: string) => Promise<UserProfile>) {
    this.cache = new InMemoryCache(5 * 60 * 1000); // 5 min TTL
    this.dbFetch = dbFetchFn;
  }

  async getProfile(userId: string): Promise<UserProfile> {
    const cacheKey = `user:${userId}`;

    const cached = this.cache.get(cacheKey);
    if (cached) return cached;

    const profile = await this.dbFetch(userId);
    this.cache.set(cacheKey, profile);
    return profile;
  }

  invalidateProfile(userId: string): void {
    this.cache.invalidate(`user:${userId}`);
  }
}
```

## **Express Middleware Approach**

```typescript
function cacheMiddleware(ttlSeconds: number = 300) {
  const cache = new InMemoryCache<any>(ttlSeconds * 1000);

  return (req: express.Request, res: express.Response, next: express.NextFunction) => {
    const cacheKey = `${req.method}:${req.originalUrl}`;

    const cached = cache.get(cacheKey);
    if (cached) {
      res.set('X-Cache', 'HIT');
      return res.json(cached);
    }

    const originalJson = res.json.bind(res);
    res.json = function (body: any) {
      cache.set(cacheKey, body);
      res.set('X-Cache', 'MISS');
      return originalJson(body);
    };

    next();
  };
}

// Usage
app.get('/api/users/:id', cacheMiddleware(300), async (req, res) => {
  const profile = await db.getUserProfile(req.params.id);
  res.json(profile);
});
```

## **Redis Cache (for distributed systems)**

```typescript
class RedisCache<T> {
  private client: redis.RedisClient;
  private ttl: number;

  constructor(redisClient: redis.RedisClient, ttlSeconds: number = 300) {
    this.client = redisClient;
    this.ttl = ttlSeconds;
  }

  async set(key: string, data: T): Promise<void> {
    await this.client.setEx(key, this.ttl, JSON.stringify(data));
  }

  async get(key: string): Promise<T | null> {
    const cached = await this.client.get(key);
    return cached ? JSON.parse(cached) : null;
  }

  async invalidate(key: string): Promise<void> {
    await this.client.del(key);
  }
}
```

**Key features:**
- ✅ Automatic TTL expiration
- ✅ Cache invalidation support
- ✅ Generic type-safe implementation
- ✅ Both sync (in-memory) and async (Redis) options
- ✅ Middleware pattern for easy integration

